ions of heresy in Jewish history, thought and literature. Contributions explore the formative role of the figure of the heretic and of heretic thought in the development of the Jewish traditions from antiquity to the 20th century. Chapters explore the role of heresy in the Hellenic period and Rabbinic literature; the significance of heresy to Kabbalah, and the critical and often formative importance the challenge of heresy plays for modern thinkers such as Spinoza, Freud, and Derrida, and literary figures such as Kafka, Tchernikhovsky, and I.B. Singer. Examining heresy as a boundary issue constitutive for the formation of Jewish tradition, this book contributes to a better understanding of the significance of the figure of the heretic for tradition more generally.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aJewish heresies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aHeresy, Jewish Identity, Canonization, Jewish Tradition.1 aAlter, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBar-On, Shraga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielik-Robson, Agata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGil, Noam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoetschel, Willi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoetschel, Willi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGruen, Erich S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIdel, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaniel, Ruth Kara-Ivanov, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagid, Shaul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatanky, Eugene D., econtributor.4ctb4https://i